<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=13&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;13</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=15&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;15&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_14.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_14.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>YOUR SINCLAIR</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>11 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
Now this is more like it! Christmas just wouldn't be Christmas without
Your Sinclair. Being a relative latecomer to the magazine fold, it
wasn't until Christmas 1986 until it got into its stride. Christmas
1984 was during its dryer Your Spectrum phase, and the only nod to the
holidays was having someone dressed up as Scrooge on the cover,
whereas Christmas 1985 was its big relaunch issue as Your Sinclair
where the festivities were pushed aside in favour of showing just how
big and new and shiny the new format was.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The rebranding was working and Your Sinclair published its first
Christmas Special at the end of 1986. It dipped its toe in quite
nicely - there was a Christmas Vox Pop, Frontlines and T'zers has a
festive theme, and there was a big (for the time) Christmas
competition.
<TABLE ALIGN="center" WIDTH=452 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d14_1984_mag5.png" target="1984_mag5.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d14_1984_mag5_small.jpg" WIDTH=106 HEIGHT=150></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d14_1986_cov4.png" target="1986_cov4.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d14_1986_cov4_small.jpg" WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=150></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d14_1987_cov4.png" target="1987_cov4.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d14_1987_cov4_small.jpg" WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=150></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d14_1990_cov2.png" target="1990_cov2.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d14_1990_cov2_small.jpg" WIDTH=106 HEIGHT=150></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=7 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>The YS Xmas Specials weren't particularly festive, but they stepped up towards the end.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/khbfL4bNcO8&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/khbfL4bNcO8&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Christmas Wrapping - Xmas at the BBC</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">This year's Christmas TV channel logos should be up and running by about now, so enjoy this Screenwipe-esque review of BBC 1 and 2 Christmas logos of years gone by. Don't miss <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ouo3KFCritQ" target="ouo3KFCritQ">part two</a> and <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jpswrAqlO-s" target="jpswrAqlO-s">part three</a> either! <b><i>(9:23)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=khbfL4bNcO8" target="khbfL4bNcO8">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/6ziha0vnwug&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/6ziha0vnwug&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>BBC Christmas Trailers 1987 - Lots Of Merry Christmasses</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Just about every BBC personality from 1987 wishes you a Merry Christmas. <b><i>(2:31)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6ziha0vnwug" target="6ziha0vnwug">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

1987's special built on that with additional Christmas features such
as the Dicing With Death board game feature, which has stuck in my
mind ever since. First, the review of the <i>Spitting Image</i> board game
("Rule One: The fattest player starts. That argument virtually
outlasted the whole game."). Secondly, the two-page spread was
bordered by its own simple board game of the "miss a go"/"go forward
two spaces" variety, and I was completely bewitched by it as this was
my first true Speccy Christmas, and everything appeared so new, fresh,
fab and funky. I wrote two computer versions of that board game - one
as a text adventure in BBC B BASIC, and one as a graphical game on the
Spectrum in BASIC, which was cruelly taken away from me by a bad SAVE
overwriting the start of the game on the tape.
<TABLE ALIGN="center" WIDTH=578 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d14_1986_mag4.png" target="1986_mag4.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d14_1986_mag4_small.jpg" WIDTH=139 HEIGHT=100></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d14_1987_mag3.png" target="1987_mag3.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d14_1987_mag3_small.jpg" WIDTH=140 HEIGHT=100></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d14_1987_mag5.png" target="1987_mag5.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d14_1987_mag5_small.jpg" WIDTH=139 HEIGHT=100></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d14_1987_yscartoon.png" target="1987_yscartoon.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d14_1987_yscartoon_small.jpg" WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=100></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=7 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>When YS went all-out for festive features, everybody won.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE><TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=135 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d14_1987_mag6.png" target="1987_mag6.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d14_1987_mag6_small.jpg" WIDTH=135 HEIGHT=200></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>YS will always be remembered fondly for this exclusive Monty Mole game, and rightly so.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
I haven't even touched on the Christmas Panto Compo, nor the Christmas
stocking fillers feature (often imitated by YS's rivals, but never
matched), and not even the humongous amount of reviews crammed into
that issue, but that wasn't all that the Christmas 1987 issue offered,
because sellotaped to the front of it was a one-off Monty Mole game
written as a Christmas card to Your Sinclair's readers. It may have
only been six simple screens, but it was so special that it's remained
a firm favourite cover game ever since.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/3J0YTOGTXMs&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/3J0YTOGTXMs&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Love Of The Common People / Paul Young</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">For <i>years</i> I didn't think of this as a Christmas song. Even the brass solo didn't give away the festive theme. Then I got digital TV and saw music channels over Christmas for the first time, and here this video was. And it's draped in tinsel and traditional festivities, and do you know the tune fits the season well? Everything clicks into place and the brass solo rounds it off quite nicely. <b><i>(5:08)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3J0YTOGTXMs" target="3J0YTOGTXMs">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

Christmas 1988 was a wonderful time for Spectrum games, and the
Christmas YS didn't disappoint. It was the largest issue ever with 150
pages, again with traditional features such as a Vox Pop, presents
guide and the like, but there was something unique about this issue -
YS had commissioned a board game of their own, and got back something
quite unique. <i>Dogfight</i> was played on a large floor using a large grid
plus eight model aeroplanes you had to make out of card. It was a
turn-based strategy game where the aim was to shoot down your
opponents planes out of the sky whilst avoiding him doing the same to
you. It was novel, intelligent, and fun to play, and ever since I've
been meaning to write a computerised version of it, complete with
computer player. Look it up and give it a try - you'll be pleasantly
surprised.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The shine may have started to go when Christmas 1989 came, but Psst
and the photo story A Heavenly Surprise rounded it off quite nicely
before Your Sinclair was sold to Future Publishing and the magic
started to die out a little but more. YS's Christmas features in the
'90s seemed a little too forced that they didn't seem to hold my
attention for too long - or maybe as I was sixteen I was maybe a bit
older than their target audience by then - but they certainly didn't
overshadow my memories of the '80s-era of Your Sinclair. The 1987 and
1988 Christmas issues were probably the two strongest issues that YS
ever produced.
</TD></TR></TABLE><p>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
</TD><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
